  function minmax(depth, maximizingPlayer) 
    if depth == 0 
      return score

    if maximizingPlayer
      maxScore = -infinity
      for each child of state:
        score = minmax(depth - 1, false)
        maxScore = max(maxScore, score)
      return maxScore

    else
      minScore = infinity
      for each child of state:
        score = minmax(depth - 1, true)
        minScore = min(minScore, score)
      return minScore
        

alpha beta pruning
  the algorithm optimizes the minmax algorithm
  it maintains 
    alpha - the minimum score that the maximizer is assured of
    beta  - the maximum score that the minimizer is assured of
  good move ordering is important for the pruning

  lets assume we are at a node for maximizer
    from one of the childs we get value 5, so we can say this node's value is >= 5,
    because the node being a maximizer will choose the highest possible value, so rn its 5
    if the next one is 4, its value still >= 5, because thats our best so for
    maybe we find something greater than 5 in other children, so for now its >= 5
    suppose the next child is 10, then our value is >= 10 depending on more children
 
    so basically we get an approx value of our node before completely searching all the children
    (this is why move ordering is good, so that we can eval good moves first which is closer to true value)

    now its >= 10, suppose rn beta value is 8, this means that a minimzer up the tree is having a child
    with value of 8, so it won't go for a node whose value is >= 10, so we dont have to search for more children
    we can prune

  same for minimizer
    from one of the children we get value 5, so we can say this node's value is <= 5
    because minimizer will choose the lowest possible value

    suppose we have an alpha value of 6, this means that a maximizer up the tree has a child of value
    6, so it will never go for this node which has a value of <= 5 so we can prune


