    function alphabeta(depth, alpha, beta, maximizingPlayer) 
      if depth == 0 
        return score

      if maximizingPlayer
        maxScore = -infinity
        for each child of state:
          score = alphabeta(depth - 1, alpha, beta, false)
          maxScore = max(maxScore, score)
          alpha = max(alpha, score)
          if (beta <= alpha)
            break
        return maxScore

      else
        minScore = infinity
        for each child of state:
          score = alphabeta(depth - 1, alpha, beta, true)
          minScore = min(minScore, score)
          beta = min(beta, score)
          if (beta <= alpha)
            break
        return minScore

negamax
  instead of having two subroutines in minmax, 
  we can use one subroutine by using the following math property

  max(x, y) = -min(-x, -y) OR min(x, y) = -max(-x, -y)

  think of it this way, each person tries to get the largest value
  and what is good for them is bad for the opponent
  and in the game of chesst your_score = -opponent_score

  so if maximizer has option 1 3 4, he will pick 4
  as minimizer instead of looking at it like min of 1 3 4, we look at it like max of -1 -3 -4, and pick
  -1, then we will return -ve of that value upawards to the maximizer

  algorithm
    function negamax(depth)
      if depth == 0
        return score

      max = -infinity
      for each child of state:
        score = -negamax(depth - 1)
        if score > max
          max = score
      return max

nega alpha beta
  just like negamax, always look to maximize, and then negate values and pass on

  alpha -> best value i can guarantee so far
  beta  -> best value for me beyond which opponent wont choose this line

  algorithm
    function negaalphabeta(depth, alpha, beta)
      if depth == 0
        return score

      best = -infinity
      for each child of state
        score = -negamax(depth -1, -beta, -alpha) // confusing part!
        best = max(best, score)
        alpha = max(alpha, score)

        if (alpha >= beta)
          break

      return best

